english:
  title: Letter to Jeong Neungsjeok, Minister of Rites, Upon His Appointment to Govern Byeokju
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have heard that you have advanced from the position of Minor Commander to that of Minister of Rites, and now take up your post in Silyeong. Surely this is cause for joy and congratulation.

    I venture to think that in advancing, you harbor the noble ambition to guide your sovereign aright, entrusting yourself to the wisdom of the great counselor. In your service, you make no distinction regarding reward, having always heeded the teachings of the noble Jillu. Your virtue shines clear and luminous, perfectly aligned with the Way.

    You are like a single jade branch upon a golden mountain reaching ten thousand fathoms high. Your brilliant reputation ascends throughout the eight seas, your splendor leisurely ascending the five clouds. As the Han chancellor transmitted the teachings that forever illuminated the halls of the learned, and as the Zhou overseer performed his duties well, so too do you uphold the honor of your house. In service to both nation and family, you embody loyalty and filial piety.

    When the Yellow Turbans threatened the palace and the imperial carriage toured the provinces, you briefly left your father's household to distant service, wielding brush and counsel to support the sovereign's will. Thus you demonstrated the loyalty of a true minister to his state.

    Now, with the sage ruler honoring the virtuous and your father graciously yielding his position, you humbly refused advancement in the military ranks yet rose gloriously in the Ministry of Rites. Like Mao Yi and Hu Wei of old, your joy cannot be contained, your virtue known to all. Thus you fulfill the filial duty owed to your family.

    Your achievements shine doubly bright, your name celebrated throughout the age. That former province is but the province it always was—how could we measure its glory differently? To leave the traveler's lodge for an official residence—this alone hardly compares. Yet now your fame rides upon the wind itself, your position screened by clouds. The standards fly high, sparing you the lament of the poet. The dragon cauldron awaits its nourishment, and you shall soon accomplish your work of salvation.

    I received your kindness from earliest days and have offered constant prayers. Though I lack the opportunity to offer formal congratulations, my admiration knows no bounds.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: '小司馬 (Minor Commander) and 大宗伯 (Minister of Rites): Official positions in the Silla administrative system'
  - key: ''
    value: '阿衡 (Ahenq): A legendary wise counselor, reference to virtuous governance'
  - key: ''
    value: '季路 (Jillu): A disciple of Confucius known for his virtue'
  - key: ''
    value: '玉樹 (Jade Branch) and 金山 (Golden Mountain): Metaphors for noble character and high virtue'
  - key: ''
    value: '黃巾 (Yellow Turbans): Referring to a historical rebellion'
  - key: ''
    value: '毛義 and 胡威: Historical exemplars of filial piety and integrity'
  - key: ''
    value: '陟岵之詩: Reference to a poem expressing filial longing'
